119. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Ovid MEDLINE(R) <2021>
ID  - 34627875
T1  - Mechanisms of action of duodenal mucosal resurfacing in insulin resistant women with polycystic ovary syndrome.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.metabol.2021.154908
A1  - Kaur, Vasha
A1  - Dimitriadis, Georgios K
A1  - Perez-Pevida, Belen
A1  - Bansi, Davinder Singh
A1  - Jayasena, Channa
A1  - Bate, Danielle
A1  - Houghton, Rhian
A1  - Fielding, Barbara A
A1  - Balfoussia, Danai
A1  - Webber, Lisa
A1  - Miao, Yun
A1  - Mears, Frederick
A1  - Jackson, Nicola
A1  - Coppin, Lucy
A1  - Perez, Jeremiah
A1  - Williams, Megan
A1  - Johnson, Brett
A1  - Umpleby, Anne Margot
A1  - Randeva, Harpal S
A1  - Miras, Alexander Dimitri
Y1  - 2021//
Y2  - 20211007//
N2  - BACKGROUND: Duodenal mucosal resurfacing (DMR) is a novel day-case endoscopic intervention which results in weight loss-independent reductions in HbA1c in patient with type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM). We hypothesized that DMR works by increasing insulin sensitivity and we aimed to investigate the mechanism of action of DMR through longitudinal metabolic phenotyping in humans., METHODS: Thirty-two insulin-resistant women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) and obesity were randomised in a double-blinded manner to DMR or sham endoscopy. They underwent measurements of insulin sensitivity using euglycaemic hyperinsulinaemic clamps, insulin secretion using oral glucose tolerance tests and reproductive function using weekly reproductive hormone profiles and ovarian ultrasonography for 6months post-intervention., RESULTS: A small increase in total body insulin sensitivity measured by the clamp was observed in both groups at week 12. An increase in insulin sensitivity, as measured by HOMA-IR, was observed in both groups at week 24. There was an increase in the number of menses (median 2 DMR, 0.5 sham). There were no significant differences between the two groups in these outcomes or insulin secretion., CONCLUSIONS: These findings suggest that DMR does not work by increasing insulin sensitivity in euglycaemic, insulin resistant women with PCOS. The procedure may exert its effects only in the context of hyperglycaemia or pathologically hyperplastic, insulin-desensitised duodenal mucosa. Copyright © 2021 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
