439. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Ovid MEDLINE(R) <2016>
ID  - 26666519
T1  - Oral carnitine supplementation reduces body weight and insulin resistance in women with polycystic ovary syndrome: a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial.
T3  - Expression of Concern in: Clin Endocrinol (Oxf). 2023 May;98(5):745 PMID: 36852455 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/36852455]
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1111/cen.13003
A1  - Samimi, Mansooreh
A1  - Jamilian, Mehri
A1  - Ebrahimi, Faraneh Afshar
A1  - Rahimi, Maryam
A1  - Tajbakhsh, Banafsheh
A1  - Asemi, Zatollah
Y1  - 2016//
Y2  - 20160129//
N1  - Expression of concern in (ECI)
N2  - OBJECTIVE: Limited data are available for evaluating the effects of oral carnitine supplementation on weight loss and metabolic profiles of women with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). This study was designed to determine the effects of oral carnitine supplementation on weight loss, and glycaemic and lipid profiles in women with PCOS., DESIGN, PATIENTS AND MEASUREMENTS: In a prospective, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial, 60 overweight patients diagnosed with PCOS were randomized to receive either 250 mg carnitine supplements (n = 30) or placebo (n = 30) for 12 weeks. Fasting blood samples were obtained at the beginning and the end of the study to quantify parameters of glucose homoeostasis and lipid concentrations., RESULTS: At the end of the 12 weeks, taking carnitine supplements resulted in a significant reduction in weight (-2.7 +/- 1.5 vs +0.1 +/- 1.8 kg, P < 0.001), BMI (-1.1 +/- 0.6 vs +0.1 +/- 0.7 kg/m(2) , P < 0.001), waist circumference (WC) (-2.0 +/- 1.3 vs -0.3 +/- 2.0 cm, P < 0.001) and hip circumference (HC) (-2.5 +/- 1.5 vs -0.3 +/- 1.8 cm, P < 0.001) compared with placebo. In addition, compared with placebo, carnitine administration in women with PCOS led to a significant reduction in fasting plasma glucose (-0.38 +/- 0.36 vs +0.11 +/- 0.97 mmol/l, P = 0.01), serum insulin levels (-14.39 +/- 25.80 vs +3.01 +/- 37.25 pmol/l, P = 0.04), homoeostasis model of assessment-insulin resistance (-0.61 +/- 1.03 vs +0.11 +/- 1.43, P = 0.04) and dehydroepiandrosterone sulphate (-3.64 +/- 7.00 vs -0.59 +/- 3.20 mumol/l, P = 0.03)., CONCLUSIONS: Overall, 12 weeks of carnitine administration in PCOS women resulted in reductions in weight, BMI, WC and HC, and beneficial effects on glycaemic control; however, it did not affect lipid profiles or free testosterone. Copyright © 2015 John Wiley & Sons Ltd.
